<p></p>
<p>This page describes which style concepts are used in our app. Since SLAM=
D makes heavy use of bootstrap, it is always a good idea to check <a href=
=3D"https://getbootstrap.com/" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">Boo=
tstrap Docs</a> for explanations and details.</p>
<p><br></p>
<h2 id=3D"StyleGuide-Pages">Pages</h2>
<ul>
<li>The app is divided into several main pages, corresponding to major feat=
ures and steps in the overall workflow.</li>
<li>Pages are accessible via the navbar or the burger menu in the navbar.</=
li>
<li>Pages are ordered left to right in logical order.</li>
<li>In special cases, major sub-features that do not fit on their parent pa=
ges may be transferred to sub-pages. These should not be accessible via the=
 navbar. (Currently the only example of this is the "Targets" page, sub-pag=
e of the "Discovery"-Page).</li>
</ul>
<h2 id=3D"StyleGuide-PageContent">Page Content</h2>
<h3 id=3D"StyleGuide-Layout">Layout</h3>
<ul>
<li>The root element of each page is a bootstrap container, to prevent the =
page from filling the full width of the screen on larger monitors.</li>
<li>Every page should be responsive, i.e. work and look pleasing on both sm=
all and large screens.</li>
<li>The elements in each page should naturally follow the workflow of the f=
eature from top to bottom.
<ul>
<li>Form elements that represent different steps and should be completed in=
 a certain natural order should be arranged top to bottom. (Example: The fi=
rst three elements on the blend page.)</li>
<li>Form elements that are "optional" or which may only be completed partia=
lly may be placed next to each other. (Example: The properties on the base =
page.)</li>
<li>If required forms are not suited to be placed on top of each other they=
 may instead be ordered horizontally from left to right. (Example: The prop=
erties selection on the Discovery page.)</li>
<li>Avoid mixing required and optional form elements in a single step.</li>
<li>Avoid mixing top-to-bottom and left-to-right flows.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Page elements are arranged in a table layout using Bootstrap's "row" an=
d "col" classes.
<ul>
<li>Pages are built from a series of rows, containing one or multiple colum=
ns. Avoid nesting rows inside columns. Keep the number of columns per row c=
onsistent on each page.</li>
<li>Use Bootstrap's gutter and margin classes to separate elements using wh=
itespace.
<ul>
<li>Use "g-3" (Gutter size 3) on rows to place gutters between row elements=
 (except there are good reasons to use a size different than 3 from a ux po=
int of view).</li>
<li>Use "mb-3" (Margin bottom size 3) to create space between row elements =
and between rows (except there are good reasons to use a size different tha=
n 3 from a ux point of view).</li>
<li>Always try to place margins below elements. Exception: Use "mt" (Margin=
 top) to create space between the first page headline and the navbar.</li>
<li>Prefer using gutters or margins of sizes 3. Exception: From a ux perspe=
ctive it makes sense to use a different size.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>
</ul></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<h3 id=3D"StyleGuide-Elements">Elements</h3>
<h4 id=3D"StyleGuide-Infoboxes">Infoboxes</h4>
<p>The functionality of each page should be explained in infoboxes.</p>
<ul>
<li>Each infobox should explain how to use the relevant elements in clear, =
concise language, explaining every step along the way. Avoid run on sentenc=
es.</li>
<li>Large infoboxes may be turned into collapsibles. (Example: Discovery pa=
ge)</li>
<li>Infoboxes may be used to improve the flow of pages by providing padding=
 and limiting the size of form elements. (Example: Blending page)</li>
</ul>
<h4 id=3D"StyleGuide-Tables">Tables</h4>
<p>Tables are the primary way of displaying data in the app.</p>
<ul>
<li>The element containing the table should generally use the "table-respon=
sive" CSS class. The table element should generally use the "table", "table=
-bordered", "table-striped", "table-hover" classes.</li>
<li>If a table is likely to be wide and tall, the container should use the =
custom "topscroll-table-container" class, and the table element should use =
the "topscroll-table" class. This will move the horizontal scrollbar of the=
 table to the top.</li>
<li>Tables should additionally be placed in accordions.</li>
</ul>
<h4 id=3D"StyleGuide-Accordions">Accordions</h4>
<p>Large page elements should be made collapsible using accordions, especia=
lly tables.</p>
<ul>
<li>Accordions should use Bootstrap's default styling. In particular, they =
should not be set to "flush".</li>
<li>Accordions containing information that the user likely needs should be =
expanded by default using "show" (Example: Base page). Large tables or thos=
e that would otherwise interfere with the layout should be collapsed by def=
ault (Example: Top of targets page).</li>
<li>If an accordion contains a table, the accordion body should be made up =
of a single div containing the "table-responsive" class. The table element =
should be immediately inside. This ensure the table is flush with the accor=
dion.</li>
</ul>
<h4 id=3D"StyleGuide-Buttons">Buttons</h4>
<p>Buttons should adhere to a consistent color scheme and have short, descr=
iptive labels.</p>
<ul>
<li>Use the following Bootstrap color classes for specific purposes:
<ul>
<li>"btn-primary" (blue) for buttons that submit, change, or add data.</li>
<li>"btn-success" (green) for buttons that stage or prepare data for the ne=
xt stage in a form (without writing anything into the session).</li>
<li>"btn-danger" (red) for buttons that delete something - either data that=
 has been staged or data that has already been written.</li>
<li>"btn-secondary" (grey) for most other actions, in particular cancellati=
ons.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Avoid using button groups.</li>
<li>Separate stages of a form using full width "btn-sucess" buttons. (Examp=
le: Blending page)</li>
<li>If placing buttons next to each other, place buttons that delete or can=
cel something to the left, and buttons that submit or proceed with somethin=
g to the right.</li>
<li>Use text on large buttons. Use icons on small, self-explanatory buttons=
.</li>
<li>Add tooltips, but do not add them to the button elements; instead, use =
wrapping divs to hold the tooltips. This way the tooltip works even if the =
button is disabled.</li>
</ul>
<h4 id=3D"StyleGuide-Alerts">Alerts</h4>
<p>Use alerts to display conditional warning or error textboxes.</p>
<ul>
<li>Use "alert-warning" to display warnings that the user may choose to ign=
ore. (Example: Blending page)</li>
<li>Use "alert-danger" to display warnings that the user needs to resolve. =
If an error occurs on the backend, use an error page instead.</li>
<li>Clearly describe the warning and how to resolve it in the textbox.</li>
</ul>
